  <h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Temperature Strategy: 2°F Makes All the Difference</strong> - Serve Bordeaux at 64-66°F to showcase its structured tannins and cassis concentration, while Burgundy performs best at 60-62°F to preserve its delicate Pinot Noir aromatics. Burgundy's volatile esters dissipate quickly above 63°F, causing you to lose those signature forest floor and cherry nuances that distinguish great Côte d'Or wines.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Decanting Logic: Bordeaux Loves Air, Burgundy Needs Finesse</strong> - Young Bordeaux (under 15 years) benefits from 2-3 hours of decanting to soften aggressive tannins and integrate oak. Mature Burgundy should only be decanted 30 minutes before serving - longer exposure can strip away the ethereal perfume that makes aged Pinot Noir magical. Never decant old Burgundy (20+ years) as it can fade within minutes.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Glass Shape Science: Bowl Geometry Changes Everything</strong> - Bordeaux requires a tall, narrow Cabernet glass to concentrate its dense fruit and manage alcohol heat, while Burgundy demands a wide, balloon-shaped Pinot Noir glass with a tapered rim to capture its expansive aromatics. The larger surface area in Burgundy glasses allows proper aeration for Pinot's delicate compounds while the inward curve traps its fleeting perfume.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Vintage Aging Curves: Know When Each Peaks</strong> - Great Bordeaux follows a predictable aging curve: drinking window opens at 8-12 years, peaks at 15-25 years, then slowly declines. Premium Burgundy is more unpredictable - it often shuts down after 5-7 years (the "dumb phase"), re-emerges beautifully at 10-15 years, then can remain sublime for decades. Track your Burgundies more carefully as they evolve in waves, not linear progression.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Food Pairing Chemistry: Fat vs. Acid Dynamics</strong> - Bordeaux's high tannins and lower acidity make it perfect for fatty red meats and aged cheeses that need astringency to cut richness. Burgundy's higher natural acidity and lower tannins pair brilliantly with duck, game birds, and mushroom dishes where you want the wine's elegance to complement, not overpower. Burgundy's acidity also makes it exceptional with salmon - something Bordeaux can't match.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Bottle Variation Reality: Burgundy's Wild Card Factor</strong> - Expect significant bottle variation in Burgundy due to smaller production lots and more hands-on winemaking - even from the same case. Bordeaux's larger-scale, more controlled production results in much more consistent bottles. When buying expensive Burgundy, purchase at least 3 bottles from the same lot to ensure you experience the wine at its best.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Investment vs. Drinking: Storage Timeline Strategy</strong> - Bordeaux from great vintages (2005, 2009, 2010, 2016) can improve for 30-50 years in proper storage, making them excellent investment wines. Most Burgundy, even from top producers, should be enjoyed within 15-20 years as Pinot Noir rarely improves beyond that point and can lose its fruit-driven charm. Buy Bordeaux to lay down, buy Burgundy to drink sooner.</li>

  <li><strong class="text-wine-700">Weather Pattern Reading: Vintage Impact Differs Dramatically</strong> - Hot vintages in Bordeaux often produce exceptional wines as Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot love warmth, while the same heat can destroy Burgundy's delicate balance. Conversely, cooler vintages that challenge Bordeaux often produce the most elegant, perfumed Burgundies. Learn to read vintage charts oppositely for these two regions - what's great for one is often challenging for the other.</li>
</ol>





  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which is more beginner-friendly: Bordeaux or Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Bordeaux is generally more beginner-friendly due to its consistent blending approach and clearer labeling by château name. The tannin structure in Bordeaux blends provides a more predictable flavor profile, while Burgundy's single-varietal Pinot Noir can vary dramatically between producers and vintages. Entry-level Bordeaux also offers better value, with quality bottles available under $30 compared to Burgundy's steeper price curve.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve Bordeaux and Burgundy at different temperatures?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, serve Bordeaux slightly warmer at 65-68°F (18-20°C) to showcase its full-bodied tannins and complex blend, while Burgundy performs best at 60-65°F (15-18°C) to preserve Pinot Noir's delicate aromatics and bright acidity. The cooler temperature for Burgundy prevents the alcohol from overwhelming its subtle terroir characteristics. Both should be opened 30-60 minutes before serving, though young Bordeaux may benefit from longer decanting.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why is Burgundy so much more expensive than Bordeaux?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Burgundy's higher prices stem from extremely limited production in tiny vineyard plots (some climats are less than 2 acres), compared to Bordeaux's larger château estates. The Côte d'Or produces roughly 10% of Bordeaux's volume, creating intense competition for bottles. Additionally, Burgundy's complex classification system includes over 600 appellations, with Premier and Grand Cru vineyards commanding premium prices due to their historical reputation and minuscule yields.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which ages better in my cellar: Bordeaux or Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Top-tier Bordeaux typically ages longer due to higher tannin levels and structured blends that can develop for 20-40 years, while most Burgundies peak within 10-20 years. However, Grand Cru Burgundies from exceptional producers like DRC or Henri Jayer can age gracefully for decades. Bordeaux's Cabernet Sauvignon backbone provides more aging insurance, but Burgundy offers more unpredictable and sometimes magical evolution when cellared properly.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying Bordeaux vs Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is applying the same purchasing logic to both regions—Bordeaux buyers should focus on château reputation and vintage quality, while Burgundy requires understanding specific vineyard sites (climats) and producer styles. Many people also assume expensive equals better in Burgundy, but exceptional values exist from lesser-known villages like Marsannay or Fixin. Vintage matters more for Bordeaux's longevity, while producer selection is crucial for Burgundy's terroir expression.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibred text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I find Bordeaux-style and Burgundy-style wines outside France?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely—California's Napa Valley produces excellent Bordeaux-style blends, while Oregon's Willamette Valley crafts outstanding Burgundian-style Pinot Noirs. Australia's Margaret River excels at Cabernet-Merlot blends, and New Zealand's Central Otago creates compelling Pinot Noir alternatives. These regions often offer better value while maintaining the essential characteristics: structured, age-worthy reds (Bordeaux-style) versus elegant, terroir-driven Pinot Noir (Burgundy-style).</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I choose between Left Bank and Right Bank Bordeaux compared to Côte de Nuits vs Côte de Beaune Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Left Bank Bordeaux (Médoc) emphasizes Cabernet Sauvignon with firmer tannins and cassis flavors, while Right Bank (Saint-Émilion, Pomerol) features Merlot's plush, earlier-drinking style. In Burgundy, Côte de Nuits produces more structured, age-worthy reds from villages like Gevrey-Chambertin, while Côte de Beaune offers more approachable, fruit-forward styles from Volnay and Beaune. Match your preference for power versus elegance to guide your choice.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
